00:01:03.247 --> 00:01:05.830
So I just want to recap some of
the most important concepts we

00:01:05.830 --> 00:01:07.340
went over.

00:01:07.340 --> 00:01:09.340
So this whole class
is essentially

00:01:09.340 --> 00:01:12.160
a study in spacetime.

00:01:12.160 --> 00:01:14.440
Later, we're going to
connect spacetime to gravity.

00:01:14.440 --> 00:01:16.148
And general relativity
is going to become

00:01:16.148 --> 00:01:18.200
the relativistic
theory of gravity.

00:01:18.200 --> 00:01:20.380
So we began with a fairly
mathematical definition.

00:01:20.380 --> 00:01:22.120
Spacetime is a
manifold of events

00:01:22.120 --> 00:01:23.860
that is endowed with a metric.

00:01:23.860 --> 00:01:26.320
Manifold, for our
purposes, is essentially

00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:28.360
just a set in
which we understand

00:01:28.360 --> 00:01:30.970
how different members of the
set are connected to each other.

00:01:30.970 --> 00:01:35.680
Events are really just when
and where something happens.

00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:37.690
We haven't precisely
defined metric yet.

00:01:37.690 --> 00:01:39.040
We will soon.

00:01:39.040 --> 00:01:41.530
But intuitively, just
regard it as some kind

00:01:41.530 --> 00:01:44.560
of a mathematical object that
gives me a notion of distance

00:01:44.560 --> 00:01:46.240
between these events.

00:01:46.240 --> 00:01:48.970
I tried and I will
continue to try

00:01:48.970 --> 00:01:50.740
to be very careful
to make a distinction

00:01:50.740 --> 00:01:52.810
between geometric
objects that live

00:01:52.810 --> 00:01:55.047
in the manifold, the
events themselves

00:01:55.047 --> 00:01:57.130
with things like a
displacement vector between two

00:01:57.130 --> 00:01:59.560
events, other
vectors, which I will

00:01:59.560 --> 00:02:01.870
recap the definition
of in just a moment.

00:02:01.870 --> 00:02:06.280
They have an existence and
sort of a reality to them

00:02:06.280 --> 00:02:09.789
that is deeper and
more fundamental

00:02:09.789 --> 00:02:12.730
than the representation
of that object.

00:02:12.730 --> 00:02:17.740
So when I say that the
displacement vector is delta t,

00:02:17.740 --> 00:02:22.090
delta x, delta y, delta z, that
is according to observer O.

00:02:22.090 --> 00:02:23.590
And when I write that down--

00:02:23.590 --> 00:02:25.830
I will be very careful
as much as possible.

00:02:25.830 --> 00:02:27.288
I will occasionally
screw this up--

00:02:27.288 --> 00:02:28.840
but I will try to
write this down

00:02:28.840 --> 00:02:31.150
without using an equal sign.

00:02:31.150 --> 00:02:33.640
Equal sign implies
a degree of reality

00:02:33.640 --> 00:02:36.110
that I do not want to impart
to that representation.

00:02:36.110 --> 00:02:38.980
So an equal dot with
a little o here,

00:02:38.980 --> 00:02:41.200
that's my personal
notation for delta

00:02:41.200 --> 00:02:44.050
x is represented
by these components

00:02:44.050 --> 00:02:47.620
according to observer O. And for
shorthand, I was sometimes just

00:02:47.620 --> 00:02:51.570
write this by the collection
of indices delta x alpha.

00:02:51.570 --> 00:02:56.710
A different observer
O bar, they will

00:02:56.710 --> 00:02:59.630
represent this this factor
using the exact same geometric

00:02:59.630 --> 00:03:00.130
object.

00:03:00.130 --> 00:03:02.920
They all agree that it's
this displacement between two

00:03:02.920 --> 00:03:04.660
physical events in spacetime.

00:03:04.660 --> 00:03:06.790
But they assign different
coordinates to it.

00:03:06.790 --> 00:03:08.800
They give a different
representation to it.

00:03:08.800 --> 00:03:12.972
And we find that representation
using a Lorenz transformation.

00:03:12.972 --> 00:03:14.680
And I'm not going to
write out explicitly

00:03:14.680 --> 00:03:16.930
the Lorenz transformation
matrix lambda.

00:03:16.930 --> 00:03:18.190
I gave it in the last lecture.

00:03:18.190 --> 00:03:21.130
And I'm assuming you're all
experts in special relativity,

00:03:21.130 --> 00:03:23.410
and I don't need
to go over that.

00:03:23.410 --> 00:03:26.320
So I will then
using this as sort

00:03:26.320 --> 00:03:29.130
of the prototype, the
general notion of a vector

00:03:29.130 --> 00:03:30.630
in spacetime, which
we'll often call

00:03:30.630 --> 00:03:32.380
a 4-vector for
the obvious reason

00:03:32.380 --> 00:03:34.900
that it has 4
components, I'm going

00:03:34.900 --> 00:03:38.557
to treat that as any quartet of
numbers that has transformation

00:03:38.557 --> 00:03:40.390
properties just like
the displacement factor

00:03:40.390 --> 00:03:41.098
I just went over.

00:03:41.098 --> 00:03:43.270
So if there's some
quantity A that

00:03:43.270 --> 00:03:46.720
has time like an x
or y and z component,

00:03:46.720 --> 00:03:50.445
as long as a different
observer, for reasons having

00:03:50.445 --> 00:03:51.820
to do with the
underlying physics

00:03:51.820 --> 00:03:53.740
or whatever the
heck this A is, as

00:03:53.740 --> 00:03:56.410
long as that different observer
relates their components

00:03:56.410 --> 00:03:59.320
to observer O's components
via the Lorenz transformation,

00:03:59.320 --> 00:04:01.600
you got yourself a 4-vector.

00:04:01.600 --> 00:04:04.958
Any random set of four
numbers, that ain't a 4-vector.

00:04:04.958 --> 00:04:07.000
You need to have some
physics associated with it.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:08.667
And the physics has
to tell it that it's

00:04:08.667 --> 00:04:10.830
a thing that's related by
a Lorenz transformation.

00:04:19.610 --> 00:04:21.110
So I want to pick
up this discussion

00:04:21.110 --> 00:04:24.410
by introducing four
particularly important

00:04:24.410 --> 00:04:27.890
and special vectors,
which to be honest,

00:04:27.890 --> 00:04:29.780
we're not going to use
too much beyond some

00:04:29.780 --> 00:04:31.970
of the first couple of
weeks or so of the course,

00:04:31.970 --> 00:04:33.000
but they're very useful.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:35.458
And one should often bear in
mind, even later in the course

00:04:35.458 --> 00:04:37.100
when they've sort
of disappeared,

00:04:37.100 --> 00:04:39.840
that they're coming along
for the ride secretly.

00:04:39.840 --> 00:04:41.570
And these are basis vectors.

00:04:47.210 --> 00:04:49.967
So if I go into frame O--

00:04:49.967 --> 00:04:52.300
I'm just going to pick some
particular reference frame--

00:04:59.770 --> 00:05:06.740
I can immediately write
down four special vectors.

00:05:06.740 --> 00:05:09.400
So remember, this is a Cartesian
type of coordinate system.

00:05:09.400 --> 00:05:13.390
So I'm going to introduce e0.

00:05:13.390 --> 00:05:15.670
I'm going to represent
this by just the number 1

00:05:15.670 --> 00:05:21.220
in the time slot and
0 everywhere else.

00:05:21.220 --> 00:05:28.130
e1, or ex if you
prefer, I'm going

00:05:28.130 --> 00:05:30.270
to write that down like so.

00:05:30.270 --> 00:05:32.490
And you can kind of see
where I'm going with this.

00:05:48.307 --> 00:05:50.890
The analogy, if you've all seen
unit vectors in other classes,

00:05:50.890 --> 00:05:52.660
hopefully this is fairly
obvious what I'm doing.

00:05:52.660 --> 00:05:54.327
I'm just picking out
a set of, you know,

00:05:54.327 --> 00:05:57.753
little dimensionless simple
quantities that point along

00:05:57.753 --> 00:05:59.170
the preferred
directions that I've

00:05:59.170 --> 00:06:01.390
set up in this inertial
reference frame.

00:06:01.390 --> 00:06:03.070
A compact way of writing this--

00:06:11.210 --> 00:06:14.730
so notice, I have
four of these vectors.

00:06:14.730 --> 00:06:18.000
And these vectors each
have four components.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:25.790
And so what I can say is that
the beta component of unit

00:06:25.790 --> 00:06:31.940
vector e alpha is
representative,

00:06:31.940 --> 00:06:37.080
according to observer O, by
delta alpha beta, the Kronecker

00:06:37.080 --> 00:06:37.580
delta.

00:06:40.550 --> 00:06:43.402
If you're not familiar
with this one,

00:06:43.402 --> 00:06:45.360
I'm usually reluctant to
send you to Wikipedia.

00:06:45.360 --> 00:06:46.985
But in this case,
I'm going to send you

00:06:46.985 --> 00:06:50.790
to Wikipedia, Wiki
via Kronecker delta.

00:06:50.790 --> 00:06:53.340
Yeah, so what that does
is it just emphasizes that

00:06:53.340 --> 00:06:54.990
at least in-- by
the way, I should

00:06:54.990 --> 00:06:58.020
put little o's underneath all
of these things, because I

00:06:58.020 --> 00:07:01.848
have chosen this according to
observer o's representation.

00:07:01.848 --> 00:07:04.140
So this is just saying that
a coin to observer O, these

00:07:04.140 --> 00:07:06.810
are four very special vectors.

00:07:06.810 --> 00:07:08.610
The utility of these things--

00:07:14.070 --> 00:07:16.070
up high for everyone in
back to be able to see--

00:07:20.210 --> 00:07:28.180
the utility of doing
this is that if I now

00:07:28.180 --> 00:07:31.720
want to write the vector
A as a geometric object,

00:07:31.720 --> 00:07:36.190
I can combine the components
that observer O uses

00:07:36.190 --> 00:07:38.637
with the basis vectors
that observer O uses.

00:07:38.637 --> 00:07:39.970
And I can sum them all together.

00:07:39.970 --> 00:07:41.290
I can put them together.

00:07:41.290 --> 00:07:43.020
And then I've got the--

00:07:43.020 --> 00:07:44.380
it's not a representation.

00:07:44.380 --> 00:07:45.470
That's a damn vector.

00:07:45.470 --> 00:07:45.970
OK?

00:07:45.970 --> 00:07:49.750
I put it all together using sort
of an internally consistent set

00:07:49.750 --> 00:07:52.360
of numbers and basis vectors.

00:07:52.360 --> 00:08:01.900
And so I am free to say
this, where I actually

00:08:01.900 --> 00:08:03.820
use an actual equal sign.

00:08:17.282 --> 00:08:18.990
You might stop and
think, well, but those

00:08:18.990 --> 00:08:21.990
aren't the components of the
observer O bar would use.

00:08:21.990 --> 00:08:23.010
And you're right.

00:08:23.010 --> 00:08:25.530
Observer O bar would not
use those components.

00:08:25.530 --> 00:08:27.850
They would also not use
those basis factors.

00:08:27.850 --> 00:08:29.940
We're going to talk about
how those things change.

00:08:29.940 --> 00:08:35.080
But observer O bar does agree
that if they were handed

00:08:35.080 --> 00:08:36.960
O's components and
O's basis vectors,

00:08:36.960 --> 00:08:39.179
this would give me a complete
representation of what

00:08:39.179 --> 00:08:40.130
the vector is.

00:08:40.130 --> 00:08:42.422
OK?

00:08:42.422 --> 00:08:44.130
So again, I'm really
harping on this sort

00:08:44.130 --> 00:08:46.200
of distinction between
the geometric object

00:08:46.200 --> 00:08:47.560
and the representation.

00:08:47.560 --> 00:08:50.075
This is the geometric object.

00:08:50.075 --> 00:08:51.792
And we can take
advantage of this.

00:08:54.390 --> 00:08:56.490
The fact that that
combination of things

00:08:56.490 --> 00:08:59.550
is the geometric object is a
tool that I'm going to now--

00:08:59.550 --> 00:09:02.340
is a fact that I'm going
to exploit in order

00:09:02.340 --> 00:09:05.460
to figure out how my
basis vectors transform

00:09:05.460 --> 00:09:06.780
when I change reference frames.

00:09:20.660 --> 00:09:29.310
So let me just repeat
what I wrote of there.

00:09:29.310 --> 00:09:42.610
But-- oops-- good point for
just a slight editorial comment.

00:09:42.610 --> 00:09:45.130
When you're talking
and writing and there

00:09:45.130 --> 00:09:47.560
are millions of little
sub scripts and indices,

00:09:47.560 --> 00:09:49.810
sometimes the brain
and the appendages

00:09:49.810 --> 00:09:51.790
get out of sync
with one another.

00:09:51.790 --> 00:09:53.560
I caught that one.

00:09:53.560 --> 00:09:54.550
I don't always.

00:09:54.550 --> 00:09:55.060
OK?

00:09:55.060 --> 00:09:56.720
So if you see
something like that

00:09:56.720 --> 00:09:59.110
and you kind of go, um, why
did that alpha magically turn

00:09:59.110 --> 00:10:00.790
into a beta, it's
probably a mistake.

00:10:00.790 --> 00:10:01.620
Please call it out.

00:10:01.620 --> 00:10:02.890
OK?

00:10:02.890 --> 00:10:08.050
All right, so this is how I
build this geometric object,

00:10:08.050 --> 00:10:09.880
using the components
and the basis

00:10:09.880 --> 00:10:13.582
vectors as measured by
O, as used by observer O.

00:10:13.582 --> 00:10:15.040
Let's now write
out what they would

00:10:15.040 --> 00:10:20.000
be if they were measured by a
different observer, an O bar

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:20.500
observer.

00:10:23.440 --> 00:10:26.500
I know how to get components,
the barred components

00:10:26.500 --> 00:10:28.030
from the unbarred components.

00:10:28.030 --> 00:10:31.900
I don't yet know how
to get the barred basis

00:10:31.900 --> 00:10:34.040
vectors from the
unbarred basis vectors.

00:10:34.040 --> 00:10:36.400
But I know that they exist.

00:10:36.400 --> 00:10:39.290
And that once I know what they
are, this equation is true.

00:10:39.290 --> 00:10:40.000
OK?

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:41.680
These are just
two different ways

00:10:41.680 --> 00:10:43.330
of writing this
geometric object, which

00:10:43.330 --> 00:10:46.750
every observer agrees
has its existence that

00:10:46.750 --> 00:10:49.420
transcends the representation.

00:10:49.420 --> 00:10:53.100
So let's rewrite what I've
got on the right-hand side

00:10:53.100 --> 00:10:55.380
of the rightmost
equal sign here.

00:10:55.380 --> 00:11:08.350
I'm going to write this as
lambda mu bar beta A beta

00:11:08.350 --> 00:11:09.230
e mu bar.

00:11:13.450 --> 00:11:16.657
And then now I'm going
to use a trick, which

00:11:16.657 --> 00:11:18.490
is what the-- it's not
even so much a trick,

00:11:18.490 --> 00:11:22.120
but I'm just going to use a
fact that is great when you're

00:11:22.120 --> 00:11:25.240
working in index notation.

00:11:25.240 --> 00:11:28.090
So often when students
first encounter

00:11:28.090 --> 00:11:30.400
this kind of notation,
your instinct

00:11:30.400 --> 00:11:32.170
is to try to write
everything out using

00:11:32.170 --> 00:11:35.110
matrices and things like row
vectors and column vectors.

00:11:35.110 --> 00:11:37.420
It's a natural thing to do.

00:11:37.420 --> 00:11:39.285
I urge you to get over that.

00:11:39.285 --> 00:11:40.660
If I get some
bandwidth for that,

00:11:40.660 --> 00:11:42.160
I'm going to write
up a set of notes

00:11:42.160 --> 00:11:45.640
this weekend showing how
one can translate at least 2

00:11:45.640 --> 00:11:47.230
by 2 objects--

00:11:47.230 --> 00:11:49.290
two index objects
and one index objects

00:11:49.290 --> 00:11:52.960
in a consistent way
between matrices and row

00:11:52.960 --> 00:11:55.300
vectors and column vectors.

00:11:55.300 --> 00:11:57.760
But we're rapidly going to
start getting into objects that

00:11:57.760 --> 00:12:00.093
are bigger than that, for
which trying to represent them

00:12:00.093 --> 00:12:02.470
in matrix-like form
gets untenable.

00:12:02.470 --> 00:12:05.045
In a little while we're going
to have a three index object.

00:12:05.045 --> 00:12:07.090
And since we don't have
three-dimensional chalkboards,

00:12:07.090 --> 00:12:09.132
making this sort of matrix
representation of that

00:12:09.132 --> 00:12:10.862
is challenging.

00:12:10.862 --> 00:12:12.820
Soon after that, we'll
have four index objects.

00:12:12.820 --> 00:12:14.778
And we'll occasionally
need to take derivatives

00:12:14.778 --> 00:12:17.260
of that four index object,
giving us a five index object.

00:12:17.260 --> 00:12:19.260
At that point, the ability
to sort of treat them

00:12:19.260 --> 00:12:21.700
like matrices is hopeless.

00:12:21.700 --> 00:12:23.710
So really, you should
just be thinking

00:12:23.710 --> 00:12:26.368
of this as ordinary
multiplication

00:12:26.368 --> 00:12:28.660
of the numbers that are
represented by these components

00:12:28.660 --> 00:12:29.760
as written out here.

00:12:29.760 --> 00:12:35.650
And an ordinary
multiplication like this,

00:12:35.650 --> 00:12:40.960
I can just go ahead and swap
the order of multiplication

00:12:40.960 --> 00:12:41.780
very easily here.

00:12:41.780 --> 00:12:47.550
So what I'm going
to do is move the--

00:12:47.550 --> 00:12:48.400
hang on a second.

00:12:51.568 --> 00:12:53.360
Yeah, yeah, yeah, now
I see what I'm doing.

00:12:53.360 --> 00:12:54.068
Sorry about that.

00:12:54.068 --> 00:12:58.200
I misread my notes.

00:12:58.200 --> 00:13:01.090
I'm just going to move
the A onto the other side

00:13:01.090 --> 00:13:01.780
of my lambda.

00:13:18.560 --> 00:13:20.540
And then I'm going
to use the fact

00:13:20.540 --> 00:13:24.380
that beta on my right-hand
side is a dummy index.

00:13:37.880 --> 00:13:40.060
So in that final expression
I wrote down over there,

00:13:40.060 --> 00:13:41.350
beta is a dummy index.

00:13:41.350 --> 00:13:43.600
And I'm free to adjust it
to put it into a form that's

00:13:43.600 --> 00:13:44.558
more convenient for me.

00:14:02.785 --> 00:14:03.410
So let's begin.

00:14:03.410 --> 00:14:05.890
Let me just write where I've
got this equation right now

00:14:05.890 --> 00:14:06.875
over there.

00:14:06.875 --> 00:14:12.220
So A alpha E alpha equals--

00:14:12.220 --> 00:14:18.740
and what I've got then is
component A beta lambda mu bar

00:14:18.740 --> 00:14:19.240
beta--

00:14:23.160 --> 00:14:24.200
keep mu bar.

00:14:24.200 --> 00:14:25.070
Sorry about that.

00:14:25.070 --> 00:14:27.490
So I'm going to
remap my dummy index.

00:14:40.260 --> 00:14:43.690
The reason I did that is I can
now move this to the other side

00:14:43.690 --> 00:14:45.195
and factor out the A alpha.

00:15:12.750 --> 00:15:14.730
OK, everyone can
see that I hope.

00:15:14.730 --> 00:15:16.530
So see what I did
was I arranged this

00:15:16.530 --> 00:15:18.780
so that I've
isolated essentially

00:15:18.780 --> 00:15:20.950
only the transformation
of the basis vector.

00:15:35.300 --> 00:15:37.910
So this equation has
to hold no matter

00:15:37.910 --> 00:15:40.420
what vector I am working with.

00:15:40.420 --> 00:15:42.260
It's got to hold for
an arbitrary A alpha.

