So the only way that
can happen, this

00:15:47.900 --> 00:15:58.380
means that my transformation
of basis vectors

00:15:58.380 --> 00:16:01.607
obeys a law that
looks like this.

00:16:01.607 --> 00:16:03.190
Now, on first
inspection, you're going

00:16:03.190 --> 00:16:04.680
to go, ah, that's
exactly what we

00:16:04.680 --> 00:16:08.010
got for the components
of the 4-vector.

00:16:08.010 --> 00:16:11.120
Caution-- I'm going
to remind you,

00:16:11.120 --> 00:16:12.900
it's actually on the
board over there.

00:16:28.770 --> 00:16:30.570
OK?

00:16:30.570 --> 00:16:34.700
The barred component is
playing a different role

00:16:34.700 --> 00:16:37.680
than the barred
basis vector here.

00:16:37.680 --> 00:16:39.330
If you want to get
the barred basis

00:16:39.330 --> 00:16:41.640
vector from the
unbarred basis vector,

00:16:41.640 --> 00:16:44.740
you need to work with the
inverse of this matrix.

00:16:44.740 --> 00:16:46.240
That's what this
is telling us here.

00:16:46.240 --> 00:16:48.180
OK?

00:16:48.180 --> 00:16:51.780
All that being said, if you're
just working through this

00:16:51.780 --> 00:16:53.347
and you've got your
components set up

00:16:53.347 --> 00:16:54.930
and you're sort of
hacking through it,

00:16:54.930 --> 00:16:57.765
the algorithm for you to
follow is actually simple.

00:17:07.130 --> 00:17:10.775
Really, all we're doing
is lining up the indices.

00:17:10.775 --> 00:17:12.650
We're summing over the
ones that are repeated

00:17:12.650 --> 00:17:14.030
and requiring that
those that are

00:17:14.030 --> 00:17:16.400
on both the left-hand side
and the right-hand side

00:17:16.400 --> 00:17:19.950
appear and equal one another.

00:17:19.950 --> 00:17:21.770
Or as an old professor
of mine liked

00:17:21.770 --> 00:17:25.990
to say about 12 times a
lecture, line up the indices.

00:17:30.560 --> 00:17:32.340
So that's essentially
what we're doing.

00:17:32.340 --> 00:17:34.670
In this case, I line up--

00:17:34.670 --> 00:17:36.503
if I have my Lorenz
transformation

00:17:36.503 --> 00:17:38.670
matrix with the barred index
up top and the unbarred

00:17:38.670 --> 00:17:39.663
down below.

00:17:39.663 --> 00:17:40.830
Boom, I line up the indices.

00:17:40.830 --> 00:17:43.080
And that tells me what the
unbarred basis components

00:17:43.080 --> 00:17:50.400
are from the barred ones, and
vice versa for the components.

00:17:50.400 --> 00:17:52.560
So what basically, as I
just said, that tells me

00:17:52.560 --> 00:17:56.250
if I actually want to get
this guy given this guy,

00:17:56.250 --> 00:17:59.590
I need to work with the inverse.

00:17:59.590 --> 00:18:01.840
Put this up high so that
everyone in the back

00:18:01.840 --> 00:18:02.340
can see it.

00:18:08.330 --> 00:18:16.140
So this, again, is one
of those places where

00:18:16.140 --> 00:18:20.850
you might be tempted to
sort of write out a matrix

00:18:20.850 --> 00:18:23.490
and do a matrix inversion.

00:18:23.490 --> 00:18:26.870
But before you do that,
remember this is physics.

00:18:26.870 --> 00:18:28.080
OK?

00:18:28.080 --> 00:18:32.040
The inverse is going to be-- the
inverse matrix is going to be

00:18:32.040 --> 00:18:35.110
the one that does, at least
for certain quantities--

00:18:35.110 --> 00:18:37.110
what the Lorenz
transformation does

00:18:37.110 --> 00:18:40.260
is that it relates
objects, if I'm at rest,

00:18:40.260 --> 00:18:42.930
if I consider myself at rest,
it tells me about things

00:18:42.930 --> 00:18:45.898
according to a frame that it's
moving with respect to me.

00:18:45.898 --> 00:18:47.440
The inverse matrix
does the opposite.

00:18:47.440 --> 00:18:48.930
It would say to
that person being

00:18:48.930 --> 00:18:51.540
at rest, what is the
matrix that tells them

00:18:51.540 --> 00:18:53.820
about things according
to me, and they

00:18:53.820 --> 00:18:56.050
see me moving with the
exact same velocity,

00:18:56.050 --> 00:18:58.360
but in the opposite direction.

00:18:58.360 --> 00:19:00.990
So to get the inverse matrix,
to get the inverse Lorenz

00:19:00.990 --> 00:19:12.250
transformation,
what we end up doing

00:19:12.250 --> 00:19:14.978
is we just reverse the velocity.

00:19:23.040 --> 00:19:25.120
So I've just wrote
down for you--

00:19:25.120 --> 00:19:27.540
and it's worth bearing in mind,
every one of these lambdas

00:19:27.540 --> 00:19:29.910
that is there, they
are really functions.

00:19:29.910 --> 00:19:44.510
And so my e alpha that
I wrote down over there,

00:19:44.510 --> 00:19:48.668
I'm going to use an under
tilde to denote a 3 vector.

00:19:48.668 --> 00:19:50.960
In one of your textbooks,
it's written with a boldface.

00:19:50.960 --> 00:19:53.235
But that's hard to
do on a blackboard.

00:19:53.235 --> 00:19:54.860
So if I want to go
the other direction,

00:19:54.860 --> 00:19:57.983
well, I just need to have
the inverse transformation.

00:20:10.820 --> 00:20:12.070
And I have that.

00:20:12.070 --> 00:20:15.670
Bear in mind, I mean, those are
really the exact same matrices.

00:20:15.670 --> 00:20:16.315
OK?

00:20:16.315 --> 00:20:18.730
In terms of the function
that I'm working with here,

00:20:18.730 --> 00:20:20.320
I'm just flipping around
the direction in order

00:20:20.320 --> 00:20:21.300
to get these things out.

00:20:21.300 --> 00:20:21.800
OK?

00:20:24.260 --> 00:20:37.770
So, as I said, you
might be tempted just

00:20:37.770 --> 00:20:42.773
to go ahead and do
the matrix inversion.

00:20:42.773 --> 00:20:44.190
Let we just do a
quick calculation

00:20:44.190 --> 00:20:47.333
to show you that
that would work.

00:20:47.333 --> 00:20:48.750
And the reason I'm
doing this is I

00:20:48.750 --> 00:20:50.917
just want to quickly step
through a particular step,

00:20:50.917 --> 00:20:54.090
which is, again, sort of in the
spirit of swatting mosquitoes

00:20:54.090 --> 00:20:56.280
with sledgehammers, it's
the kind of analysis

00:20:56.280 --> 00:20:58.572
that you're going to sort of
have to do off to the side

00:20:58.572 --> 00:21:00.060
now and again.

00:21:00.060 --> 00:21:05.340
So given that I
know e alpha is--

00:21:05.340 --> 00:21:08.060
let's see, let's use beta--

00:21:08.060 --> 00:21:14.390
e beta bar be e beta bar.

00:21:14.390 --> 00:21:24.020
But I now know that I could
write this guy as lambda--

00:21:24.020 --> 00:21:25.980
let's use a gamma--

00:21:25.980 --> 00:21:33.425
beta bar minus v in
the gamma direction.

00:21:33.425 --> 00:21:35.300
Now, you look at that,
and you go, ooh, look,

00:21:35.300 --> 00:21:38.730
I'm actually summing
over the betas there.

00:21:38.730 --> 00:21:41.048
Let's gather my terms a
little bit differently.

00:21:56.690 --> 00:22:01.830
So notice, I have unbarred basis
vectors over here on the left,

00:22:01.830 --> 00:22:04.140
unbarred ones over
