00:23:27.460 --> 00:23:29.540
just by using them in a
slightly different order.

00:23:29.540 --> 00:23:30.850
OK?

00:23:30.850 --> 00:23:35.290
All right, so far all still
basically just formulas.

00:23:35.290 --> 00:23:39.980
So I'm going to start now doing
a little bit of formalism that

00:23:39.980 --> 00:23:41.918
will very quickly
segue into physics.

00:23:41.918 --> 00:23:43.460
We can all take a
deep sigh of relief

00:23:43.460 --> 00:23:45.560
and go, ah, OK, something
you can imagine measuring.

00:23:45.560 --> 00:23:46.185
So that's nice.

00:23:49.080 --> 00:23:53.360
So I have introduced 4-vectors.

00:23:53.360 --> 00:23:55.860
I haven't introduced the basis
vectors and their components.

00:23:55.860 --> 00:23:58.800
I haven't really done
anything with them yet.

00:23:58.800 --> 00:24:00.810
So before we start
doing things with them,

00:24:00.810 --> 00:24:02.190
let's think about
some operations

00:24:02.190 --> 00:24:04.560
that we can do with 4-vectors.

00:24:04.560 --> 00:24:07.830
So the first one which
I'd like to introduce

00:24:07.830 --> 00:24:08.685
is a scalar product.

00:24:13.670 --> 00:24:15.710
To motivate the scalar
product that I'm

00:24:15.710 --> 00:24:21.800
going to define in the same
way that I defined 4-vectors

00:24:21.800 --> 00:24:25.490
as a quartet of numbers whose
transformation properties

00:24:25.490 --> 00:24:29.210
are based on the transformation
properties of the displacement,

00:24:29.210 --> 00:24:31.730
I'm going to motivate
a general scalar

00:24:31.730 --> 00:24:37.280
product between 4-vectors by a
similar kind of quantity that

00:24:37.280 --> 00:24:39.570
is constructed from
the displacement.

00:24:39.570 --> 00:24:41.660
So let me recall a
result that I hope

00:24:41.660 --> 00:24:44.074
is familiar from
special relativity.

00:24:48.720 --> 00:25:01.750
So working in units where
the speed of light is 1,

00:25:01.750 --> 00:25:03.610
you are hopefully all
familiar with the fact

00:25:03.610 --> 00:25:07.150
that this quantity
is something that is

00:25:07.150 --> 00:25:09.260
in variance to all observers.

00:25:09.260 --> 00:25:11.200
I did not use a
represented by symbol

00:25:11.200 --> 00:25:13.570
there, because no matter
whose delta t, delta

00:25:13.570 --> 00:25:15.820
x, delta y, delta
z I use there, they

00:25:15.820 --> 00:25:21.190
will all agree on the delta s
squared that comes out of this.

00:25:21.190 --> 00:25:22.578
If I want to--

00:25:22.578 --> 00:25:24.370
actually, let me write
of a few things done

00:25:24.370 --> 00:25:25.630
before I say anything more.

00:25:25.630 --> 00:25:27.430
So this is an invariant.

00:25:37.010 --> 00:25:37.805
This is the same--

00:25:39.967 --> 00:25:42.550
let me actually write this in a
slightly different way-- it is

00:25:42.550 --> 00:25:44.550
the same in all Lorenz frames.

00:25:56.960 --> 00:26:02.090
So pick some observer, get their
delta t, delta x, et cetera,

00:26:02.090 --> 00:26:04.760
assemble delta s squared,
pick a different observer,

00:26:04.760 --> 00:26:08.090
do the Lorenz transformation,
assemble their delta t prime,

00:26:08.090 --> 00:26:12.350
delta x prime, et cetera, make
that, boom, they all agree.

00:26:12.350 --> 00:26:15.290
So we're going to
use this to say,

00:26:15.290 --> 00:26:19.340
you know what, I'm going to
call that the inner product

00:26:19.340 --> 00:26:21.080
of the displacement
vector with itself.

00:26:29.630 --> 00:26:37.510
So I'm going to call this
delta x dotted into delta x.

00:26:37.510 --> 00:26:42.185
And so what this means is that
built into my scalar product--

00:26:44.950 --> 00:26:48.140
so if I write this as
a particular observer

00:26:48.140 --> 00:26:49.265
would compute it--

00:27:01.792 --> 00:27:03.250
this is the scalar
product that I'm

00:27:03.250 --> 00:27:06.455
going to define with respect
to the displacement vector.

00:27:06.455 --> 00:27:08.830
And this is usually the point
where somebody in the class

00:27:08.830 --> 00:27:11.290
is thinking, why is
there a minus sign

00:27:11.290 --> 00:27:12.790
in front of the timelike piece?

00:27:17.800 --> 00:27:19.810
I can't answer that.

00:27:19.810 --> 00:27:22.320
All I can say is
that appears to be--

00:27:22.320 --> 00:27:23.320
more than appears to be.

00:27:23.320 --> 00:27:26.090
There's a whole frickin' butt
load of evidence-- that's

00:27:26.090 --> 00:27:27.817
not how nature is assembled.

00:27:27.817 --> 00:27:29.650
OK, it's connected to
the fact-- so the fact

00:27:29.650 --> 00:27:31.630
that all of my
spatial directions

00:27:31.630 --> 00:27:33.550
are sort of entered
with the same sign,

00:27:33.550 --> 00:27:37.780
but my timelike direction,
it has a different sign.

00:27:37.780 --> 00:27:40.060
It's connected to the fact
that I can easily move

00:27:40.060 --> 00:27:41.863
left and right, front and back.

00:27:41.863 --> 00:27:43.030
It's a little bit of effort.

00:27:43.030 --> 00:27:44.980
I can move up and down.

00:27:44.980 --> 00:27:48.760
But I cannot say, oh, crap, I
left my phone at home I'll go

00:27:48.760 --> 00:27:50.470
back 15 minutes and pick it up.

00:27:50.470 --> 00:27:53.170
You cannot move back
and forth in time.

00:27:53.170 --> 00:27:55.480
Time actually, which is
the timelike component

00:27:55.480 --> 00:27:57.515
of this thing, it
enters into the geometry

00:27:57.515 --> 00:27:59.890
in a fundamentally different
way from the spatial things.

00:27:59.890 --> 00:28:02.830
And that's reflected
in that minus sign.

00:28:02.830 --> 00:28:06.580
Anything deeper than
that, let's just

00:28:06.580 --> 00:28:09.700
say that we're probably
not likely to get very

00:28:09.700 --> 00:28:11.560
far with that conversation.

00:28:11.560 --> 00:28:13.390
Depending on what kind
of muscle relaxants

00:28:13.390 --> 00:28:14.940
you enjoy using on
the weekend, you

00:28:14.940 --> 00:28:16.810
might have some fun
conversations about it.

00:28:16.810 --> 00:28:19.525
But it is not something
that you're really

00:28:19.525 --> 00:28:20.650
going to get very far with.

00:28:20.650 --> 00:28:21.640
You just kind of have
to accept that it's

00:28:21.640 --> 00:28:23.470
part of the built-in
geometry of nature.

00:28:27.040 --> 00:28:31.110
OK, so this I am defining
as the inner products

00:28:31.110 --> 00:28:33.990
of the displacement
vector with itself.

00:28:33.990 --> 00:28:37.350
I define vectors as having the
same transformation properties

00:28:37.350 --> 00:28:38.550
as the displacement vector.

00:29:02.830 --> 00:29:06.490
We can similarly define an
inner product of a 4-vector

00:29:06.490 --> 00:29:07.020
with itself.

00:29:10.275 --> 00:29:12.400
OK, now, I'll put
this on another board.

00:29:32.310 --> 00:29:38.040
So A dot A, I'm going
to define this--

00:29:38.040 --> 00:29:40.530
or rather I will say it
is represented according

00:29:40.530 --> 00:29:53.760
to observer O as minus A0
squared plus A1 squared plus A2

00:29:53.760 --> 00:29:59.470
squared plus A3 squared.

00:29:59.470 --> 00:30:01.470
I realize there can be a
little bit of ambiguity

00:30:01.470 --> 00:30:03.200
in the way I'm writing it here.

00:30:03.200 --> 00:30:04.250
You just have to--

00:30:04.250 --> 00:30:06.450
if you're ever confused,
just ask for clarification

00:30:06.450 --> 00:30:08.520
about whether I'm writing
something to a power

00:30:08.520 --> 00:30:11.070
or whether it's an index label.

00:30:11.070 --> 00:30:13.050
Context usually makes it clear.

00:30:13.050 --> 00:30:17.730
Handwriting sometimes
obscures context though.

00:30:17.730 --> 00:30:20.880
The reason why I'm doing this
and a real benefit of this

00:30:20.880 --> 00:30:23.130
is that whatever
this quantity is,

00:30:23.130 --> 00:30:26.100
because A has the
same transformation

00:30:26.100 --> 00:30:28.650
properties of the
displacement, this must

00:30:28.650 --> 00:30:30.450
be a Lorenz invariant as well.

00:30:41.730 --> 00:30:44.040
The underlying mathematics
of Lorenz transformation

00:30:44.040 --> 00:30:46.980
doesn't care that I wrote a
zero instead of delta x here.

00:30:46.980 --> 00:30:49.980
It doesn't care that I wrote A1
instead of delta x1, et cetera.

00:30:49.980 --> 00:30:51.480
It just knows that
it's a thing that

00:30:51.480 --> 00:30:53.940
goes into that slot of
the Lorenz transformation.

00:30:53.940 --> 00:30:56.220
So all observers-- this
is how I represent it

00:30:56.220 --> 00:31:01.325
according to observer O. But all
observers agree on that form.

00:31:01.325 --> 00:31:03.450
And as a consequence, this
is going to be something

00:31:03.450 --> 00:31:05.670
that we exploit a lot.

00:31:05.670 --> 00:31:07.830
Even when we move beyond
the simple geometry

00:31:07.830 --> 00:31:10.230
of special relativity,
a generalization of this

00:31:10.230 --> 00:31:15.280
will be extremely important
for, not an exaggeration to say,

00:31:15.280 --> 00:31:17.530
everything.

00:31:17.530 --> 00:31:19.247
So a little bit of terminology--

00:31:23.360 --> 00:31:31.210
so if A dot A is negative, and
depending upon which is bigger,

00:31:31.210 --> 00:31:33.550
A0 squared or the sum
of the other ones--

00:31:33.550 --> 00:31:35.500
it could very well be negative--

00:31:35.500 --> 00:31:38.590
we say that A is a
time like vector.

00:31:43.950 --> 00:31:46.130
This traces back to
the fact that if A

00:31:46.130 --> 00:31:49.850
were the displacement
vector, if the displacement,

00:31:49.850 --> 00:31:52.610
the invariant interval, were
negative that would tell me

00:31:52.610 --> 00:31:54.943
that the two events, which
are the beginning and the end

00:31:54.943 --> 00:31:57.290
of the interval, I could
find a frame at which they're

00:31:57.290 --> 00:32:01.033
at the exact same location and
are only separated in time.

00:32:01.033 --> 00:32:02.450
In the same way,
this is basically

00:32:02.450 --> 00:32:03.980
saying that I can
find a frame when

00:32:03.980 --> 00:32:08.180
this vector points parallel
to some observer's time axis.

00:32:13.916 --> 00:32:19.070
If this is positive,
A is spacelike.

00:32:22.850 --> 00:32:25.430
Everything I just said about
timelike, lather, rinse,

00:32:25.430 --> 00:32:27.903
repeat, but replace
time with space.

00:32:27.903 --> 00:32:28.403
OK?

00:32:31.840 --> 00:32:37.780
And if A dot A equals
0, we say A is--

00:32:37.780 --> 00:32:41.160
there's two words that
are commonly used--

00:32:41.160 --> 00:32:45.580
lightlike or null.

00:32:48.160 --> 00:32:50.200
Null just traces back
obviously to the zero.

00:32:50.200 --> 00:32:54.280
Lightlike is because this is a
vector that could lie tangent

00:32:54.280 --> 00:32:58.136
to the trajectory that a light
beam follows in spacetime.

00:32:58.136 --> 00:32:58.636
OK?

00:33:23.780 --> 00:33:26.520
OK, let me get some clean chalk.

00:33:29.930 --> 00:33:32.240
So, so far, I've only talked
about this inner product,

00:33:32.240 --> 00:33:33.680
this scalar product.

00:33:33.680 --> 00:33:37.340
Oh, and, by the way, I'll
use inner product and scalar

00:33:37.340 --> 00:33:40.035
products somewhat
interchangeably.

00:33:40.035 --> 00:33:41.660
But this allows me
to reiterate a point

00:33:41.660 --> 00:33:43.070
I made in Tuesday's lecture.

00:33:43.070 --> 00:33:47.270
When I say scalar, scalar
refers to a quantity which is--

00:33:47.270 --> 00:33:49.770
you know, it doesn't have any
components associated with it.

00:33:49.770 --> 00:33:52.312
So in that sense, it's familiar
from your eager intuition of,

00:33:52.312 --> 00:33:53.758
you know, not to vector.

00:33:53.758 --> 00:33:55.550
But it has a deeper
meaning in this course,

00:33:55.550 --> 00:33:56.540
because I also want
it to be something

00:33:56.540 --> 00:33:58.910
that is invariant
between reference frames.

00:33:58.910 --> 00:34:01.100
So A dot A is the
scalar product.

00:34:01.100 --> 00:34:04.280
It gives me a quantity that
all observers agree on.

00:34:04.280 --> 00:34:06.860
Now, I've only done
scalar products

00:34:06.860 --> 00:34:09.020
of vectors, A and the
displacement vector,

00:34:09.020 --> 00:34:10.460
with themselves.

00:34:10.460 --> 00:34:22.949
So a more general notion,
if I have vectors A and B,

00:34:22.949 --> 00:34:25.409
then I will define the
inner product between them,

00:34:25.409 --> 00:34:30.510
as observed by O, as constructed
by observer O, rather, like so.

00:34:43.190 --> 00:34:44.732
It's not hard to
convince yourself,

00:34:44.732 --> 00:34:46.190
given everything
we've done so far,

00:34:46.190 --> 00:34:49.605
that this quantity
must also be invariant.

00:34:49.605 --> 00:34:50.980
I'll sketch a
really quick proof.

00:34:58.570 --> 00:35:01.060
Let's define-- let's say
we have two 4-vectors, A

00:35:01.060 --> 00:35:06.760
and B. Their sum, by
the linearity rules that

00:35:06.760 --> 00:35:09.530
apply to these vectors,
must also be a vector.

00:35:09.530 --> 00:35:17.620
And so if I compute, C dot
C, this is an invariant.

00:35:17.620 --> 00:35:27.340
With a little bit of
labor, that basically

00:35:27.340 --> 00:35:31.100
boils down to middle
school algebra.

00:35:31.100 --> 00:35:33.570
You can show that C dot
C is A dot A plus B dot B

00:35:33.570 --> 00:35:37.270
plus twice A dot B.
This is invariant.

00:35:37.270 --> 00:35:39.070
This is invariant.

00:35:39.070 --> 00:35:40.000
This is invariant.

00:35:40.000 --> 00:35:42.760
And so this must be invariant.

00:35:49.010 --> 00:35:53.068
So this is really useful for
us, because we now have a way--

00:35:53.068 --> 00:35:55.360
I've introduced these objects,
these geometric objects,

00:35:55.360 --> 00:35:56.480
these 4-vectors.

00:35:56.480 --> 00:35:59.760
We are going to use
them in this class

00:35:59.760 --> 00:36:01.920
to describe quantities
that are of interest

00:36:01.920 --> 00:36:05.040
to the physicist who wants to
make measurements in spacetime.

00:36:05.040 --> 00:36:06.498
We've now learned
one of the things

00:36:06.498 --> 00:36:08.040
when you're doing
stuff in relativity

00:36:08.040 --> 00:36:10.270
is you have to be careful
who is measuring what.

00:36:10.270 --> 00:36:12.630
What are the components
that 4-vector as seen

00:36:12.630 --> 00:36:14.038
by this observer?

00:36:14.038 --> 00:36:16.580
What about their friend who's
jogging through the room at 3/4

00:36:16.580 --> 00:36:17.340
quarters speed of light?

00:36:17.340 --> 00:36:19.243
What about their friend who's
driving 2/3 the speed of light

00:36:19.243 --> 00:36:20.010
in the other direction?

00:36:20.010 --> 00:36:22.343
You have all these really
annoying calculations that you

00:36:22.343 --> 00:36:24.660
can and sometimes have to do.

00:36:24.660 --> 00:36:26.820
This gives us a way to
get certain things that

00:36:26.820 --> 00:36:28.350
are invariant out
of the situation

00:36:28.350 --> 00:36:30.830
that everyone is
going to agree on.

00:36:30.830 --> 00:36:32.250
Invariants are our friends.

00:36:42.360 --> 00:36:44.860
So earlier today, earlier
in today's lecture,

00:36:44.860 --> 00:36:48.480
I talked about how I can write
my 4-vectors using the basis

00:36:48.480 --> 00:36:49.500
factors.

00:36:49.500 --> 00:36:51.410
So another way of writing this--

00:36:51.410 --> 00:36:54.390
so what's sort of annoying
is every time I've actually

00:36:54.390 --> 00:36:56.970
written out the inner product,
I have used the represented

00:36:56.970 --> 00:36:58.890
by symbol.

00:36:58.890 --> 00:36:59.640
I don't want that.

00:36:59.640 --> 00:37:01.900
I want to have equal
symbols in there, dammit.

00:37:01.900 --> 00:37:09.390
So let's take advantage
of the fact that A dot B,

00:37:09.390 --> 00:37:13.240
I know how to expand A and
B using components and basis

00:37:13.240 --> 00:37:13.740
vectors.

00:37:25.770 --> 00:37:27.790
And again, using
the index notation,

00:37:27.790 --> 00:37:29.670
I can just pull everything
out and rearrange

00:37:29.670 --> 00:37:30.420
this a little bit.

00:37:43.588 --> 00:37:45.380
Whenever you get down
to a point like this,

00:37:45.380 --> 00:37:48.500
we now get to do what every
mathematician loves to do--

00:37:48.500 --> 00:37:50.360
give something a name.

00:37:50.360 --> 00:37:53.750
I'm going to define the
inner product of basis vector

00:37:53.750 --> 00:38:01.800
A with basis vector B to
be a two index tensor--

00:38:01.800 --> 00:38:03.840
eta alpha beta.

00:38:06.910 --> 00:38:12.430
What's lovely about this, this
is a totally frame invariant

00:38:12.430 --> 00:38:12.940
quantity.

00:38:12.940 --> 00:38:14.060
We know that.

00:38:14.060 --> 00:38:18.060
And so I've now found a way to
write this using the components

00:38:18.060 --> 00:38:20.350
as something that gives me
a result that is totally

00:38:20.350 --> 00:38:21.435
frame invariant.

00:38:21.435 --> 00:38:23.060
Now, when you hack
through a little bit

00:38:23.060 --> 00:38:24.820
the algebra of this,
what you'll find

00:38:24.820 --> 00:38:27.220
is that the components
of this metric--

00:38:27.220 --> 00:38:29.610
oh, shoot, I didn't want to
actually say it out loud--

00:38:29.610 --> 00:38:31.802
the components of this
tensor, which pretend

00:38:31.802 --> 00:38:33.010
you didn't hear me say that--

00:38:33.010 --> 00:38:37.208
the components of this tensor
has the following components--

00:38:37.208 --> 00:38:39.625
I just said something circular--
has the following values.

00:38:49.250 --> 00:38:52.130
This is, as I
unfortunately gave away

00:38:52.130 --> 00:38:55.010
the plot, this is,
in fact, the metric

00:38:55.010 --> 00:38:58.250
that I said at the beginning
is the quantity that I must

00:38:58.250 --> 00:38:59.810
associate with
spacetime in order

00:38:59.810 --> 00:39:02.210
for there to be a notion
of distance between events.

00:39:12.510 --> 00:39:15.137
I haven't really said what
a tensor is carefully yet.

00:39:15.137 --> 00:39:17.220
I'm going to make a more
formal definition of this

00:39:17.220 --> 00:39:18.040
in just a moment.

00:39:18.040 --> 00:39:19.623
But this is your
first example of one.

00:39:23.150 --> 00:39:26.020
And so the way in
which this actually

00:39:26.020 --> 00:39:29.170
gives me a notion of
distance is through this

00:39:29.170 --> 00:39:31.360
that I wrote down right here.

00:39:31.360 --> 00:39:37.840
If I have two
events in spacetime

00:39:37.840 --> 00:39:49.410
that are separated by
a displacement delta x,

00:39:49.410 --> 00:39:55.770
the delta s squared, which
I obtained from this thing,

00:39:55.770 --> 00:39:59.160
is fundamentally the notion
of distance between those two

00:39:59.160 --> 00:40:00.420
events that I use.

00:40:00.420 --> 00:40:03.450
And notice, it's a little
less normal of a distance

00:40:03.450 --> 00:40:04.950
than you're used
to when you do sort

00:40:04.950 --> 00:40:06.400
of ordinary Euclidean geometry.

00:40:06.400 --> 00:40:09.786
This is a distance whose
square can be negative.

00:40:20.480 --> 00:40:22.370
What we like to say
is that when you're

00:40:22.370 --> 00:40:26.960
working in special
relativity, it's

00:40:26.960 --> 00:40:29.480
not necessarily positive-- the
distance between two events

00:40:29.480 --> 00:40:31.480
is not necessarily-- the
distance squared is not

00:40:31.480 --> 00:40:34.162
necessarily positive definite.

00:40:34.162 --> 00:40:35.870
If it's negative,
though, that just means

00:40:35.870 --> 00:40:38.390
it's sort of dominated by the
time interval between them.

00:40:38.390 --> 00:40:40.640
If it's positive, you know
it's dominated by the space

00:40:40.640 --> 00:40:41.900
interval between them.

00:40:41.900 --> 00:40:44.375
If it's zero, well,
you actually know--

00:40:44.375 --> 00:40:46.500
it's actually a little bit
confusing at that point.

00:40:46.500 --> 00:40:48.490
They could be, in
fact, you know,

00:40:48.490 --> 00:40:51.380
very widely separated
in both space and time,

00:40:51.380 --> 00:40:54.080
but in such a way that a
light beam could connect them.

00:40:54.080 --> 00:40:57.940
So there's a lot of
information encoded in that.

00:40:57.940 --> 00:41:00.832
Now, as we move forward--

00:41:00.832 --> 00:41:02.540
hang on a second--

00:41:02.540 --> 00:41:08.020
as we move forward, we're
going to upgrade this.

00:41:08.020 --> 00:41:12.760
So right now, our metric
is just this simple matrix

00:41:12.760 --> 00:41:17.160
of minus 1s, 0s, and 1s.

00:41:17.160 --> 00:41:19.180
One of things that
we're going to do

00:41:19.180 --> 00:41:22.700
is sort of a warm-up exercise
to the more complicated things

00:41:22.700 --> 00:41:24.750
we're going to do
later is we're going

00:41:24.750 --> 00:41:26.737
to move away from
special relativity

00:41:26.737 --> 00:41:27.820
and Cartesian coordinates.

00:41:27.820 --> 00:41:29.160
We're going to look at
it in polar coordinates.

00:41:29.160 --> 00:41:31.118
That's going to be kind
of like a warm-up zone.

00:41:31.118 --> 00:41:33.790
And so when we do
that, we're always

00:41:33.790 --> 00:41:38.740
going to reserve eta for the
metric of special relativity

00:41:38.740 --> 00:41:40.920
when I'm working in
Cartesian coordinates.

00:41:40.920 --> 00:41:42.670
It's just a great
symbol to have for that.

00:41:42.670 --> 00:41:44.320
And it's a useful
thing to always

00:41:44.320 --> 00:41:47.130
have that definition in mind.

00:41:47.130 --> 00:41:49.030
I can continue to do
special relativity,

00:41:49.030 --> 00:41:50.710
but then working in
coordinates that are, you know,

00:41:50.710 --> 00:41:53.050
spherical-like or polar-like
or something like that,

00:41:53.050 --> 00:41:55.960
then this is going
to become a function.

00:41:55.960 --> 00:41:58.000
And what that is
going to mean is

00:41:58.000 --> 00:41:59.680
that things like my
little basis vector

00:41:59.680 --> 00:42:02.580
is going to have more
complicated behavior.

00:42:02.580 --> 00:42:04.330
A little later in the
course, we will then

00:42:04.330 --> 00:42:08.380
show that when gravity
enters into the picture,

00:42:08.380 --> 00:42:09.910
essentially the
essence of gravity

00:42:09.910 --> 00:42:12.670
is going to be encoded in
this thing as well in a way

00:42:12.670 --> 00:42:14.420
where, again, it's
going to be a function.

00:42:14.420 --> 00:42:16.810
It's going to vary as a
function of space and time.

00:42:16.810 --> 00:42:19.175
And the dynamics of gravity
will be buried in that.

00:42:19.175 --> 00:42:21.550
It's sort of funny that it
really does just sort of start

00:42:21.550 --> 00:42:22.050
out--

00:42:22.050 --> 00:42:24.940
I mean, if you take that thing
and you set delta t equals 0,

00:42:24.940 --> 00:42:27.100
this is just the bloody
Pythagorean theorem.

00:42:27.100 --> 00:42:30.820
That is all this is.

00:42:30.820 --> 00:42:33.430
Put time back in, and it
sort of is the generalization

00:42:33.430 --> 00:42:35.055
of Pythagoras to spacetime.

00:42:35.055 --> 00:42:37.180
And, in fact, we're going
to take advantage of that

00:42:37.180 --> 00:42:39.610
and sort of define
a geometry that

00:42:39.610 --> 00:42:41.698
looks like this as being
flat in the same way

00:42:41.698 --> 00:42:43.990
that a board is flat, and
the Pythagorean theorem works

00:42:43.990 --> 00:42:45.258
perfectly on it.

00:42:45.258 --> 00:42:47.050
Then, we're going to
start think about what

00:42:47.050 --> 00:42:48.370
happens when it becomes curved.

00:42:48.370 --> 00:42:49.420
And you start
thinking about things

00:42:49.420 --> 00:42:51.920
like, what is the geometry on
the surface of the sphere look

00:42:51.920 --> 00:42:52.432
like?

00:42:52.432 --> 00:42:53.890
That's just sort
of pointing ahead.

00:42:53.890 --> 00:42:55.557
So I just throw that
at you, so that you

00:42:55.557 --> 00:42:57.520
get ready for some
of the concepts

00:42:57.520 --> 00:43:01.090
that we'll be
talking about soon.

