that I've introduced is
the displacement vector.

00:50:57.470 --> 00:51:00.020
From the displacement
vector, it's really easy

00:51:00.020 --> 00:51:02.180
to make the probably
the first and simplest

00:51:02.180 --> 00:51:10.270
important 4-vector, which
is known as the 4-velocity.

00:51:14.570 --> 00:51:18.140
This tells me the rate of
displacement of an observer

00:51:18.140 --> 00:51:22.032
as this person moves
through spacetime per unit--

00:51:22.032 --> 00:51:24.365
and we're going to be careful
about this in this class--

00:51:26.870 --> 00:51:39.410
d tau is the time
interval as measured

00:51:39.410 --> 00:51:53.400
along the trajectory of the
observer with 4-velocity u.

00:51:53.400 --> 00:51:56.370
In other words-- that's a very
long winded way of saying it--

00:51:56.370 --> 00:51:58.440
it's an interval of proper time.

00:52:09.840 --> 00:52:12.323
In English, the word proper
time sounds very like, woo,

00:52:12.323 --> 00:52:13.740
I don't want to
use improper time.

00:52:13.740 --> 00:52:14.572
I better use that.

00:52:14.572 --> 00:52:16.530
But this actually I think
it comes from French.

00:52:16.530 --> 00:52:19.680
It just refers to the fact
that it's one's own time.

00:52:19.680 --> 00:52:21.780
Apparently in German
people say eigenzeit.

00:52:21.780 --> 00:52:24.420
So, you know, there's a couple
of different words for it.

00:52:24.420 --> 00:52:27.703
But proper time is what we use.

00:52:27.703 --> 00:52:29.370
In special relativity,
if we see someone

00:52:29.370 --> 00:52:35.410
going by with constant velocity,
a particular observer who sees,

00:52:35.410 --> 00:52:36.020
you know--

00:52:36.020 --> 00:52:36.770
we're here in the room.

00:52:36.770 --> 00:52:37.687
Someone comes through.

00:52:37.687 --> 00:52:39.170
Their 4-velocity is u.

00:52:39.170 --> 00:52:42.350
We would see their 4-velocity
to have the components

00:52:42.350 --> 00:52:48.290
gamma gamma v, where
gamma, I'll remind you,

00:52:48.290 --> 00:52:52.750
is the special
relativistic Lorenz factor.

00:52:52.750 --> 00:52:57.200
And I'll remind you again
we've set speed of light to 1.

00:52:57.200 --> 00:53:00.220
A very useful thing,
which we're actually

00:53:00.220 --> 00:53:03.760
going to take advantage
of quite a bit,

00:53:03.760 --> 00:53:07.750
is that in the rest frame of u--

00:53:24.795 --> 00:53:25.920
pardon me for a second--

00:53:28.550 --> 00:53:34.200
in the rest frame
of u, or I should

00:53:34.200 --> 00:53:47.922
say of the observer
whose 4-velocity is u,

00:53:47.922 --> 00:53:51.340
they just have 1 in
atomic direction, C,

00:53:51.340 --> 00:53:53.760
if you want to put your
factors back into their.

00:53:53.760 --> 00:53:56.260
And that's basically just saying
that the person is standing

00:53:56.260 --> 00:54:01.000
still, but moving through
time, because you are always

00:54:01.000 --> 00:54:03.160
moving through time.

00:54:03.160 --> 00:54:10.600
All right, from the 4-velocity
for an observer who has--

00:54:10.600 --> 00:54:13.870
or for an object, I should
say, who has some mass,

00:54:13.870 --> 00:54:24.160
we can easily define
the 4-momentum,

00:54:24.160 --> 00:54:28.540
where this m is known as the
rest mass of this object.

00:54:36.921 --> 00:54:40.820
It's worth a bit of
description here.

00:54:40.820 --> 00:54:43.430
You will often see, particularly
in some older textbooks that

00:54:43.430 --> 00:54:44.860
discuss special
relativity, people

00:54:44.860 --> 00:54:48.330
like to talk about
the relativistic mass.

00:54:48.330 --> 00:54:50.480
And that comes from the
fact that if I write out

00:54:50.480 --> 00:54:52.640
what this thing
looks like according

00:54:52.640 --> 00:55:02.540
to some particular observer,
you have this gamma m entering

00:55:02.540 --> 00:55:03.890
into both of the components.

00:55:03.890 --> 00:55:05.660
And so older
textbooks often called

00:55:05.660 --> 00:55:08.390
gamma m the relativistic mass.

00:55:08.390 --> 00:55:10.348
That's not really
the way people have--

00:55:10.348 --> 00:55:12.140
over the course of the
past couple decades,

00:55:12.140 --> 00:55:14.900
they've moved away from that.

00:55:14.900 --> 00:55:17.930
And it's just more useful
to focus on the rest mass

00:55:17.930 --> 00:55:19.703
as the only really
meaningful mass,

00:55:19.703 --> 00:55:21.120
because, as we'll
see in a moment,

00:55:21.120 --> 00:55:23.180
it's a Lorenz invariant.

00:55:23.180 --> 00:55:27.207
We'll see how that is in
literally about 3 minutes.

00:55:27.207 --> 00:55:28.790
And so what we're
instead going to say

00:55:28.790 --> 00:55:33.360
is that as seen by some
particular observer,

00:55:33.360 --> 00:55:35.100
this has a timelike
component that

00:55:35.100 --> 00:55:38.490
is the energy that that
observer would measure

00:55:38.490 --> 00:55:40.470
and a set of
spacelike components

00:55:40.470 --> 00:55:42.720
that are the momentum that
that observer will measure.

00:55:45.890 --> 00:55:48.470
So where we get a bit of
important physics out of all

00:55:48.470 --> 00:55:53.128
this stuff is by coupling these
two 4-vectors to the scalar

00:55:53.128 --> 00:55:54.170
products that we made up.

00:56:07.210 --> 00:56:12.550
So the first one,
if you do u dot u,

00:56:12.550 --> 00:56:14.110
according to any
observer, that's

00:56:14.110 --> 00:56:18.340
just going to be
minus gamma squared

00:56:18.340 --> 00:56:21.300
plus gamma squared v squared.

00:56:25.690 --> 00:56:28.390
And with about 20 seconds
worth of analysis,

00:56:28.390 --> 00:56:33.826
you can find that this is
always equal to minus 1.

00:56:38.020 --> 00:56:41.390
Actually, there's an even
trickier way to do this.

00:56:41.390 --> 00:56:44.980
Suppose I evaluate this in
the rest frame of the observer

00:56:44.980 --> 00:56:46.690
whose 4-velocity is u?

00:56:46.690 --> 00:56:50.380
Well, in the rest frame,
v is 0, and gamma is 1,

00:56:50.380 --> 00:56:51.800
and I get minus 1.

00:56:51.800 --> 00:56:53.080
And this is an invariant.

00:56:53.080 --> 00:56:55.120
So whatever I get in
that particular frame

00:56:55.120 --> 00:56:57.285
must be obtained in all frames.

00:56:57.285 --> 00:56:58.660
That's a trick
we're going to use

00:56:58.660 --> 00:56:59.868
over and over and over again.

00:56:59.868 --> 00:57:01.645
Sometimes you can identify--

00:57:01.645 --> 00:57:03.820
you know, you get some kind
of God awful expression

00:57:03.820 --> 00:57:04.960
that just makes
you want to vomit.

00:57:04.960 --> 00:57:06.460
But then you go,
wait a minute, what

00:57:06.460 --> 00:57:08.667
would this look like in
frame blah, blah, blah?

00:57:08.667 --> 00:57:10.750
And you sort of think about
some particular frame.

00:57:10.750 --> 00:57:13.780
And in that frame,
it may simplify.

00:57:13.780 --> 00:57:17.890
And if it does and it's a frame
invariant quantity, mazel tov,

00:57:17.890 --> 00:57:19.960
you have just basically
won the lottery.

00:57:19.960 --> 00:57:22.360
You've got this
all taken care of.

00:57:22.360 --> 00:57:24.610
Go on with your life.

00:57:24.610 --> 00:57:29.120
So the 4-velocity has a
scalar product of itself

00:57:29.120 --> 00:57:30.510
that is always minus 1.

00:57:30.510 --> 00:57:31.010
OK?

00:57:37.365 --> 00:57:40.810
How about the 4-momentum?

00:57:40.810 --> 00:57:45.370
Well, the 4-momentum is
just 4-velocity times mass.

00:58:07.600 --> 00:58:10.240
So that's just minus m squared.

00:58:10.240 --> 00:58:12.870
But we also know it's related
to these two other quantities,

00:58:12.870 --> 00:58:14.430
which are important in physics.

00:58:14.430 --> 00:58:17.260
This is related to the
energy and to the momentum.

00:58:17.260 --> 00:58:20.760
So this is also equal to
minus e squared plus--

00:58:24.860 --> 00:58:28.340
so this is the ordinary 3--

00:58:28.340 --> 00:58:31.010
the magnitude of the 3-vector
part of this thing as

00:58:31.010 --> 00:58:34.760
measured by the
observer who breaks up

00:58:34.760 --> 00:58:37.040
the 4-momentum in this way.

00:58:37.040 --> 00:58:39.800
So what this means is I
can manipulate this guy

00:58:39.800 --> 00:58:40.970
around a little bit here.

00:58:52.710 --> 00:58:55.060
Anybody who works
in particle physics

00:58:55.060 --> 00:58:56.810
is presumably familiar
with this equation.

00:58:56.810 --> 00:58:58.435
Sometimes it appears
with the p squared

00:58:58.435 --> 00:59:00.160
moved onto the other side.

00:59:00.160 --> 00:59:02.650
If it looks a little
bit unfamiliar to you,

00:59:02.650 --> 00:59:06.690
let me put some factors
of C back in this.

00:59:06.690 --> 00:59:08.810
So remember, we have
set C equal to 1.

00:59:17.560 --> 00:59:20.860
When you put it back
in, that's what this is.

00:59:20.860 --> 00:59:23.320
So it drops out of this in
a very, very simple way.

00:59:26.330 --> 00:59:28.840
One of the uses of this--

00:59:28.840 --> 00:59:31.450
and many of you have
done exercises presumably

00:59:31.450 --> 00:59:33.200
in some previous
study that does this.

00:59:33.200 --> 00:59:38.277
And there'll be one
exercise on the p set

00:59:38.277 --> 00:59:40.110
that was just posted
where you exploit this.

00:59:43.620 --> 00:59:45.270
So a key bit of
physics, the reason

00:59:45.270 --> 00:59:50.430
why we care about 4-momentum is
it's in one mathematical object

00:59:50.430 --> 00:59:52.440
allows us to combine
conservation energy

00:59:52.440 --> 00:59:53.730
and conservation of momentum.

01:00:01.460 --> 01:00:06.617
So conservation of 4-momentum
puts both conservation

01:00:06.617 --> 01:00:08.200
of energy and
conservation of momentum

01:00:08.200 --> 01:00:10.340
into one mathematical object.

01:00:10.340 --> 01:00:20.900
So if I have n
particles that interact,

01:00:20.900 --> 01:00:39.143
then the total 4-momentum is
conserved in the interaction.

01:00:45.765 --> 01:00:46.720
OK?

01:00:46.720 --> 01:00:50.637
So, yeah, we talk a
little bit more about this

01:00:50.637 --> 01:00:52.220
and then just sort
of quickly move on.

01:00:52.220 --> 01:00:56.370
So combining this
with the fact that we

01:00:56.370 --> 01:00:59.702
are free to change our
reference frames often

01:00:59.702 --> 01:01:01.910
it gives us a trick that
allows us to really simplify

01:01:01.910 --> 01:01:03.190
a lot of analysis.

01:01:07.420 --> 01:01:09.005
So if I have n
particles that are

01:01:09.005 --> 01:01:10.380
sort of swarming
around and doing

01:01:10.380 --> 01:01:16.470
some horrible bit of
business that I need to study

01:01:16.470 --> 01:01:22.020
and I need to have a
good understanding of,

01:01:22.020 --> 01:01:37.780
we can often vastly
simplify our algebra

01:01:37.780 --> 01:01:41.372
by choosing a special and very
convenient frame of reference

01:01:41.372 --> 01:01:42.580
in which to do our analysis--

01:01:46.340 --> 01:01:48.270
choose the center
of momentum frame.

01:01:54.920 --> 01:02:00.255
So this is the time frame
in which that that p tote--

01:02:04.190 --> 01:02:06.786
so C-O-M, center of momentum--

01:02:09.910 --> 01:02:12.060
has zero spatial momentum.

01:02:12.060 --> 01:02:14.830
In that frame, you have just as
much momentum going to the left

01:02:14.830 --> 01:02:16.872
as going to the right,
just as much going forward

01:02:16.872 --> 01:02:19.300
as going backwards, as much
going up as going down.

01:02:19.300 --> 01:02:22.930
And so this turns out to be--
so the classic example of where

01:02:22.930 --> 01:02:29.592
this is really useful is when
you are studying particle

01:02:29.592 --> 01:02:32.050
collisions and you're looking
at things like the production

01:02:32.050 --> 01:02:33.253
of new particles.

01:02:44.860 --> 01:02:50.660
So imagine you've got particle
A with some 4-momentum PA coming

01:02:50.660 --> 01:02:52.130
in like this.

01:02:52.130 --> 01:02:56.030
Particle B's got some
4-momentum coming in like this.

01:02:56.030 --> 01:02:58.310
These guys collide.

01:02:58.310 --> 01:02:59.270
And they do so--

01:02:59.270 --> 01:03:00.950
I work in the center
of momentum frame.

01:03:00.950 --> 01:03:04.490
I might want to just calculate
the energy at which they just

01:03:04.490 --> 01:03:10.440
happen to produce some new
pair of particles at rest.

01:03:10.440 --> 01:03:11.880
I would like to
find the threshold

01:03:11.880 --> 01:03:14.290
for this particular
creation process.

01:03:14.290 --> 01:03:14.790
OK?

01:03:14.790 --> 01:03:16.457
So you're going to
play with one problem

01:03:16.457 --> 01:03:18.950
on the p-set that's
kind of like that.

01:03:18.950 --> 01:03:20.630
Let's see, what do
I have time to do?

01:03:20.630 --> 01:03:21.500
I think I will do--

01:03:24.655 --> 01:03:26.280
yeah, I think I can
do two more things.

01:03:36.010 --> 01:03:43.710
So all the dot products that I
have been talking about so far

01:03:43.710 --> 01:03:47.640
have been a dot product
of a 4-vector with itself.

01:03:47.640 --> 01:03:49.050
I did u dotted into u.

01:03:49.050 --> 01:03:51.240
I did p dotted into p.

01:03:51.240 --> 01:03:54.240
I invented a frame in which p
has a particularly simple form.

01:03:54.240 --> 01:03:56.198
And then when you actually
do some of analysis,

01:03:56.198 --> 01:03:59.213
you would probably take that
p tote and dot it into itself.

01:03:59.213 --> 01:04:00.630
I haven't done
anything that looks

01:04:00.630 --> 01:04:03.570
at the crossing between
these two things,

01:04:03.570 --> 01:04:07.435
dotting one into the other.

01:04:07.435 --> 01:04:11.450
So let me to go through
a very useful result that

01:04:11.450 --> 01:04:14.570
follows by combining p with u.

01:04:14.570 --> 01:04:16.730
There's a very
specific notion of p

01:04:16.730 --> 01:04:18.140
and a very specific notion of u.

01:04:40.340 --> 01:04:44.900
Let's let p be the
4-momentum of a particle.

01:04:44.900 --> 01:04:45.470
I call it a.

01:04:58.780 --> 01:05:13.190
Let's let u be the 4-velocity
not of a, but the 4-velocity

01:05:13.190 --> 01:05:22.902
of observer O. So
particle a might

01:05:22.902 --> 01:05:24.860
be a muon that was created
the upper atmosphere

01:05:24.860 --> 01:05:26.960
and is crashing through
our room right now.

01:05:26.960 --> 01:05:29.780
Observer O might be
your hyperactive friend

01:05:29.780 --> 01:05:33.245
who is jogging through the room
at half the speed of light.

01:05:33.245 --> 01:05:39.530
The question I want to ask
is, what does O measure

01:05:39.530 --> 01:05:45.705
as the energy of particle a.

01:06:11.630 --> 01:06:14.060
So the naive way to do
this, which I will emphasize

01:06:14.060 --> 01:06:18.320
is not wrong, what you
might do is sort of go,

01:06:18.320 --> 01:06:20.210
OK, well, we're sitting here.

01:06:20.210 --> 01:06:22.140
This room is our laboratory.

01:06:22.140 --> 01:06:23.910
I've measure this
thing in my lab.

01:06:23.910 --> 01:06:26.480
So I know p as I measure it.

01:06:26.480 --> 01:06:28.280
I can see O jogging by.

01:06:28.280 --> 01:06:32.180
So I know O's 4-velocity
as I measure it.

01:06:32.180 --> 01:06:35.390
So what I should do is figure
out the Lorenz transformation

01:06:35.390 --> 01:06:38.720
that takes me into
the rest frame of O.

01:06:38.720 --> 01:06:40.658
Once I have that
Lorenz transformation,

01:06:40.658 --> 01:06:42.200
I'll apply that
Lorenz transformation

01:06:42.200 --> 01:06:44.510
to the 4-vector p.

01:06:44.510 --> 01:06:47.030
Boom, that will
give me that energy.

01:06:47.030 --> 01:06:47.960
That will work.

01:06:47.960 --> 01:06:49.070
That will absolutely work.

01:06:52.652 --> 01:06:54.110
But there's an
easier way to do it.

01:06:57.760 --> 01:07:11.010
So one thing you should note is
that everybody represents that

01:07:11.010 --> 01:07:17.636
4-velocity as an energy--

01:07:17.636 --> 01:07:19.760
excuse me, they
represent the 4-momentum

01:07:19.760 --> 01:07:21.573
as an energy and a 3-momentum.

01:07:21.573 --> 01:07:23.240
In particular, though,
they represent it

01:07:23.240 --> 01:07:26.030
as the energy that
they would measure

01:07:26.030 --> 01:07:30.440
and the 3-momentum that
they would measure.

01:07:30.440 --> 01:07:39.730
So that means p as seen
by O is e according to O

01:07:39.730 --> 01:07:48.545
and p according to O. That are
acquainted o is what we want.

01:07:48.545 --> 01:07:49.920
And I just told
you a moment ago,

01:07:49.920 --> 01:07:52.208
you know, if you have p in
your own reference frame,

01:07:52.208 --> 01:07:54.000
and you have u in your
own reference frame,

01:07:54.000 --> 01:07:56.250
you can do this whole math
with Lorenz transformations

01:07:56.250 --> 01:07:57.000
and get it out.

01:07:57.000 --> 01:08:05.930
But you also know that in
O's own reference frame,

01:08:05.930 --> 01:08:15.770
O represents their 4-velocity as
1 in the timelike direction, 0

01:08:15.770 --> 01:08:17.135
in the spatial direction.

01:08:25.550 --> 01:08:31.420
So what this means is if I
go into O's reference frame,

01:08:31.420 --> 01:08:42.140
if I go into their
inertial reference frame,

01:08:42.140 --> 01:08:45.710
notice that if I take the
dot product of p and u,

01:08:45.710 --> 01:08:49.275
I get e times 1 and p times 0.

01:09:00.130 --> 01:09:02.439
So that is just negative.

01:09:02.439 --> 01:09:05.207
It's exactly what I
want-- modulo minus sign.

01:09:05.207 --> 01:09:07.540
And so you go, OK, well, I'll
flip my minus sign around.

01:09:13.359 --> 01:09:15.069
And you think, OK,
great, but I did

01:09:15.069 --> 01:09:17.170
that using those
quantities as written down

01:09:17.170 --> 01:09:18.640
in O's reference frame.

01:09:18.640 --> 01:09:20.680
And then you go,
holy crap, that's

01:09:20.680 --> 01:09:23.109
the invariant scalar product.

01:09:23.109 --> 01:09:23.810
I'm done.

01:09:23.810 --> 01:09:24.310
Mic drop.

01:09:24.310 --> 01:09:26.080
Leave the room.

01:09:26.080 --> 01:09:31.000
What this means is you start
with p as you measure it,

01:09:31.000 --> 01:09:33.399
u as you measure it.

01:09:33.399 --> 01:09:35.680
Take the scalar product
between the two of them.

01:09:35.680 --> 01:09:37.840
Boom, the answer
you want pops out.

01:09:37.840 --> 01:09:39.910
No nonsense of Lorenz
transformations.

01:09:39.910 --> 01:09:42.194
None of that garbage
needs to happen.

01:09:42.194 --> 01:09:44.319
You just take that inner
product and you've got it.

01:10:27.760 --> 01:10:29.970
So that sort of says
in words, no matter

01:10:29.970 --> 01:10:32.565
what representation you choose
to write down p and u in,

01:10:32.565 --> 01:10:34.440
take the dot product
between the two of them,

01:10:34.440 --> 01:10:37.500
throw in a minus sign, you've
got the energy of the particle

01:10:37.500 --> 01:10:39.840
with p as measured by
the observer with u.

01:10:44.660 --> 01:10:47.810
It's sort of late in the
hour, or the hour and a half

01:10:47.810 --> 01:10:48.930
I should say.

01:10:48.930 --> 01:10:51.060
So let me just
sort of emphasize,

01:10:51.060 --> 01:10:54.080
there are occasional
moments in this class where

01:10:54.080 --> 01:10:58.130
if you're dozing off a little
bit, I suggest you pop up

01:10:58.130 --> 01:11:00.800
and tattoo this into
a neuron somewhere.

01:11:00.800 --> 01:11:02.090
This is one of those moments.

01:11:02.090 --> 01:11:02.330
OK?

01:11:02.330 --> 01:11:04.670
This is a result that we're
going to use over and over

01:11:04.670 --> 01:11:06.380
and over again,
because this holds--

01:11:06.380 --> 01:11:08.840
this isn't just in
